# Network communication
Network communication requires 3 classes: HTTPClient, URLSessionProvider and a Request. A client class holds a reference of a provider which in turn holds an url session that is created using the provider. The request encapsulates a URLRequest object (urlRequest) with all required information for sending requests such as httpMethod or parameter.

# URLSessionProvider
URLSessionProvider is responsible to provide us the url session object that we can use throughout our project by creating it only once when we initialize our HTTPClient class which holds this provider. This avoids any memory leaks. We also provide the initializer with a custom session configuration that allows us to disable certificate validation and create an insecure URLSessionConfiguration as a default for legacy devices. We override URLSessionConfiguration class in our project by providing our custom configurations and we pass it down into our provider initializer. This way we avoid unnecessary warnings that comes when we try to connect to a secure http server with a non secure url session configuration object.

# Request
A request encapsulates the urlRequest object required for sending network requests such as httpMethod or parameters. The init takes an instance of urlSessionProvider and a string url which can be either a cloud URL (https://api.example.com)  or a localURL(http://192.168.x.x). We override the initializer to provide default values for parameters, httpMethod etc. It also has a property named requestBuilder where we create and configure the urlRequest object with parameters passed in. Finally a property called httpRequest to pass along the request to the provider’s URLSession object that is initialized at a higher level of abstraction.